
TY  - JOUR
T1  - Preferential Linkage and Network Evolution: A Conceptual Model and Empirical Test in the U.S. Video Game Sector
AU  - Venkatraman, N.
AU  - Lee, Chi-Hyon
Y1  - 2004/12/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/20159628
DO  - 10.5465/20159628
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 876
EP  - 892
VL  - 47
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We examined how network structure (density overlap and embeddedness) and technology characteristics of a platform (dominance and newness) shaped interorganizational coordination of product launches in the U.S. video game industry. We found that the developers' choices to launch games for particular game consoles were significantly explained by these four factors using multiprobability regression on a primary data set of 2,815 launches between 1995 and 2002. This analysis was complemented with application of a network visualization technique.
AB  - We examined how network structure (density overlap and embeddedness) and technology characteristics of a platform (dominance and newness) shaped interorganizational coordination of product launches in the U.S. video game industry. We found that the developers' choices to launch games for particular game consoles were significantly explained by these four factors using multiprobability regression on a primary data set of 2,815 launches between 1995 and 2002. This analysis was complemented with application of a network visualization technique.
