TY  - JOUR
T1  - Partner Substitutability, Alliance Network Structure, and Firm Profitability in the Telecommunications Industry
AU  - Bae, Jonghoon
AU  - Insead, Martin Gargiulo
Y1  - 2004/12/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/20159626
DO  - 10.5465/20159626
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 843
EP  - 859
VL  - 47
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This paper explores the effects of partner substitutability and alliance network structure on organizational profitability. Although firms are expected to benefit from the exclusive resources brought in by resource-rich, nonsubstitutable alliance partners, the costs of allying with such partners could offset those benefits. Analyzing alliances in the U.S. telecommunications industry, we show that a firm facing nonsubstitutable partners was better off when its alliances were embedded in third-party ties, which allowed the firm to gain indirect leverage on such partners.
AB  - This paper explores the effects of partner substitutability and alliance network structure on organizational profitability. Although firms are expected to benefit from the exclusive resources brought in by resource-rich, nonsubstitutable alliance partners, the costs of allying with such partners could offset those benefits. Analyzing alliances in the U.S. telecommunications industry, we show that a firm facing nonsubstitutable partners was better off when its alliances were embedded in third-party ties, which allowed the firm to gain indirect leverage on such partners.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/20159626
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/20159626
