TY  - JOUR
T1  - How Do They Get There? An Examination of the Antecedents of Centrality in Team Networks
AU  - Klein, Katherine J.
AU  - Lim, Beng-Chong
AU  - Saltz, Jessica L.
AU  - Mayer, David M.
Y1  - 2004/12/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/20159634
DO  - 10.5465/20159634
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 952
EP  - 963
VL  - 47
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Drawing on social exchange and similarity-attraction theories, we hypothesized that individuals' demographic characteristics, values, and personality influence their acquisition of central positions in their teams' social networks. Education and neuroticism predicted centrality five months later; individuals who were highly educated and low in neuroticism became high in advice and friendship centrality and low in adversarial centrality. Team members' values similarity to their teammates also predicted advice and friendship centrality; demographic similarity had limited effects.
AB  - Drawing on social exchange and similarity-attraction theories, we hypothesized that individuals' demographic characteristics, values, and personality influence their acquisition of central positions in their teams' social networks. Education and neuroticism predicted centrality five months later; individuals who were highly educated and low in neuroticism became high in advice and friendship centrality and low in adversarial centrality. Team members' values similarity to their teammates also predicted advice and friendship centrality; demographic similarity had limited effects.
