TY  - JOUR
T1  - Two's Company, Three's a Crowd? Triads in Cooperative-Competitive Networks
AU  - Madhavan, Ravindranath
AU  - Gnyawali, Devi R.
AU  - He, Jinyu
Y1  - 2004/12/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/20159631
DO  - 10.5465/20159631
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 918
EP  - 927
VL  - 47
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Triadic structure is an important, but neglected, aspect of interfirm networks. We developed the constructs clustering and countering as potential drivers of triadic structure and combined them with the recently developed p* network model to demonstrate the value and feasibility of triadic analysis. Exploratory analysis of data from the global steel industry revealed firms' tendency to form transitive triads, in which three firms all have direct ties with each other, especially within blocks defined by geography or technology.
AB  - Triadic structure is an important, but neglected, aspect of interfirm networks. We developed the constructs clustering and countering as potential drivers of triadic structure and combined them with the recently developed p* network model to demonstrate the value and feasibility of triadic analysis. Exploratory analysis of data from the global steel industry revealed firms' tendency to form transitive triads, in which three firms all have direct ties with each other, especially within blocks defined by geography or technology.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/20159631
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/20159631
Y2  - 2026/04/24
